prj:ScienceGoal.prj:name: Field 1 - Tuning 1
prj:ScienceGoal.prj:note: This Science Goal is for the first set of sources (Field 1) and is tuning 1 of 5. This science goal is to measure the redshifts of 35 sources predicted to be in the redshift range 3<z<4 by covering most of Band 3 (3mm). All sources are within 10 degrees of each other. (see Technical description to see why a separate science goal was used per tuning rather than spectral-scan mode)

prj:TechnicalJustification.prj:justificationText:
This project is to find redshifts for galaxies predicted to have redshifts in the range 3<z<4. To achieve this we need the widest possible bandwidth and so perform 5 separate overlapping tunings each with 1875 MHz bandwidth to cover the region between 84.2 GHz and 113.4 GHz. Initially we tried to use spectral-scan mode to schedule all 5 tunings in one Science Goal but found it was far less efficient than scheduling each tuning separately (~6x difference). We used the exact tunings created by the spectral-scan mode for our individual science blocks.
We are using the correlator mode with 1875 MHz bandwidth and 0.98 MHz frequency resolution, but then with a factor 16 spectral averaging to give a 7.8 MHz frequency resolution equivalent to ~23 km/s at our frequencies. We choose this mode over the coarse frequency resolution (~93 km/s), which would give us ~6 elements per line width, as it gives us the flexibility to look at brighter-lines in more detail (~20 resolution elements), while retaining the ability to bin the data to our intended 90 km/s (our lines are expected to have a width between 500-800 km/s). The data rates in this setup are very modest at 1.5 MB/s.

All of our sources are predicted to be at a redshift of 3<z<4 and so the largest possible source scale is ~3 arcsecond, easily below the largest angular scales for relative compact configurations in Band 3 (3mm). As this is not a mapping experiment at the is stage we request a modest spatial resolution of 1" in order to just resolve the gravitational lens.

This project is to find redshifts for galaxies predicted to have redshifts in the range 3<z<4. To achieve this we need the widest possible bandwidth and so perform 5 separate tunings each with 1875 MHz bandwidth to cover the region between 84.2 GHz and 113.4 GHz. Initially we tried to use spectral-scan mode to schedule all 5 tunings in one Science Goal but found it was far less efficient than scheduling each tuning separately (~6x difference). We used the exact tunings created by the spectral-scan mode for our individual science blocks.
All of the sources for this Science Goal (Field 1) are within 10 degrees on the sky so a single calibration can be used. Our sensitivity of 1.5 mJy per 90 km/s window is chosen so that in a 90 km/s channel we expect to have a 3 sigma detection for all our targets, and a 7-9 sigma detection when including all the channels in the line (assuming a line width of 500-800 km/s). This value was calculated by using line fluxes from previously observed lensed objects and scaling for our SPIRE 500um flux limit of 65 mJy. Our sensitivity estimates should ensure we are enable to detect emission lines from all of our sources.
While continuum is not the main aim of this experiment by combining all five tunings we will achieve a continuum sensitivity of 43 micro-Jy and so should detect our targets.

prp:ObsProposal.prp:abstract: We propose to measure redshifts for 58 submillimetre sources in the redshift range 3 < z < 4, using a technique designed to increase the efficiency of ALMA as a redshift engine by a factor of ~5. Our survey will increase the number of submillimetre sources known in this redshift range by a factor of four and will be the first systematic statistical study of the dusty Universe 1-2 billion years after the Big Bang, providing a vital counterpart to the optical surveys of the Universe in this epoch.
